arockstar:
I would suggest to use ng-constant (npm install grunt-ng-constant) in Gruntfile.js that will create a js file with defined angular constants. Let’s configure ng constans:
javascript
grunt.initConfig({
ngconstant: {
  options: {
    name: 'config',
    dest: '<application path>/scripts/config.js',
    wrap: '"use strict";\n\n <%= __ngModule %>'
  },
  development: {
    constants: {
      isProduction: false
    }
  },
  production: {
    constants: {
      isProduction: true
    }
  }
}
});
Next, we need to add relevant constant to each grunt task:
javascript
grunt.registerTask('build', [ ... 'ngconstant:production', ... ]);
grunt.registerTask('test-dev', [ ... 'ngconstant:development', ... ]);
After it created module with constants (config.js) should be injected into application and we can use it as dependency. 
Here we have an area for thoughts: how to encapsulate needed information (what environment we are currently running) in easier (optimal) way, within minimum number lines of code and operations.
For raw example we can write somewhere in bootstrap.js: isProduction = isProduction || false  and remove isProduction:false in development configuration of ng-constants section.
Or we can define new constant isDevelopment to let us be more flexible in case if other environments will appear in the universe.
